<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,152,1058]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis box="[198,330,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Greek 
<emphasis box="[545,609,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">citrin</emphasis>
“lemon” and Latin 
<emphasis box="[857,981,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">maculosus</emphasis>
“spotted,” in reference to the yellow integumental maculations on tergum II.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,152,1058]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis box="[198,301,952,977]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is known only from the female. It is easily identified by the four yellow maculae on tergum II, the conspicuous 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[521,571,991,1017]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">“Y”</emphasis>
-shaped pattern of silver setae on the dorsum of the mesosoma, and the body coarsely sculptured throughout.
</paragraph>
